 ###### 
From cou.: 1 The assessment of matrix effects in the quantification of organophosphorus pesticides in fruit and vegetables by GC-NPD, were studied applying ANCOVA. Calibration curves prepared in solvent were compared with calibration curves prepared in a blank matrix extract for eight different commodities, establishing whether the matrix induces systematic or proportional errors in the quantification of the pesticides. In such cases correction functions were obtained and validated by quantifying spiked samples using solvent calibrations and applying the correction functions to the data obtained. The results were compared with those obtained by quantification using matrix-matching calibrations and with those from 100% recovery experiments. It was found that the matrix effects can be avoided using the correction functions. Finally the contribution of the correction functions to the uncertainty of the results was estimated as well as their stability during a four month period.
From Soup: 1 The assessment of matrix effects in the quantification of organophosphorus pesticides in fruit and vegetables by GC-NPD , were studied applying ANCOVA. Calibration curves prepared in solvent were compared with calibration curves prepared in a blank matrix extract for eight different commodities, establishing whether the matrix induces systematic or proportional errors in the quantification of the pesticides . In such cases correction functions were obtained and validated by quantifying spiked samples using solvent calibrations and applying the correction functions to the data obtained. The results were compared with those obtained by quantification using matrix-matching calibrations and with those from 100% recovery experiments. It was found that the matrix effects can be avoided using the correction functions. Finally the contribution of the correction functions to the uncertainty of the results was estimated as well as their stability during a four month period.
 ###### 
From cou.: 2 Control programmes on pesticide residue levels are carried out by official and private analytical laboratories to ensure the quality of fruits and vegetables in order to reduce the risk to the consumer.1–4 In this field, the analytical problem has two aspects: on the one hand there is a need to determine a wide range of pesticides in a single run or as fast as possible, because the products are perishable and the number of samples use to be high; on the other hand there is a need to achieve reliability in the determination of such residues, at the low concentration levels established by the legislation as the maximum residue levels (MRLs)5,6 allowed. Both aspects must involve low costs and low environmental contamination (for example, reduction in solvent consumption), but must also have accuracy and representativeness.
From Soup: 2 Control programmes on pesticide residue levels are carried out by official and private analytical laboratories to ensure the quality of fruits and vegetables in order to reduce the risk to the consumer. 1–4 In this field, the analytical problem has two aspects: on the one hand there is a need to determine a wide range of pesticides in a single run or as fast as possible, because the products are perishable and the number of samples use to be high; on the other hand there is a need to achieve reliability in the determination of such residues, at the low concentration levels established by the legislation as the maximum residue levels (MRLs) 5,6 allowed. Both aspects must involve low costs and low environmental contamination (for example, reduction in solvent consumption), but must also have accuracy and representativeness.
 ###### 
From cou.: 3 The first aspect, which is mainly related to additional analytical properties,7 is usually achieved with multiresidue methods.8–10 The ideal multiresidue method requires little sample treatment and minimises reagent consumption but it should be feasible to determine as many analytes as possible. Accuracy, which is among the principal analytical properties, is achieved working in a quality system that ensures the sensitivity, selectivity and precision required. Both objectives have to be balanced depending on the goal of the analytical process.
From Soup: 3 The first aspect, which is mainly related to additional analytical properties, 7 is usually achieved with multiresidue methods. 8–10 The ideal multiresidue method requires little sample treatment and minimises reagent consumption but it should be feasible to determine as many analytes as possible. Accuracy, which is among the principal analytical properties, is achieved working in a quality system that ensures the sensitivity, selectivity and precision required. Both objectives have to be balanced depending on the goal of the analytical process.
 ###### 
From cou.: 4 A key aspect in pesticide multiresidue methods is their selectivity. The definition of this term is being revised by IUPAC,11 who recommend its use for referring to the extent to which a given method can determine particular analytes under given conditions in mixtures or matrices, simple or complex, without interferences from other components. In the context of pesticide multiresidue methods the definition of selectivity relates to the matrix effects and/or the presence of interferences. Massart et al.12 distinguish between interferences (for example, co-elution of two compounds in a chromatographic method) and matrix effects, which may affect the analytical signal by increasing the level of random errors and/or introducing a systematic effect on the analytical results (which can be either constant, affecting the blank, or proportional, affecting the analytical sensitivity).
From Soup: 4 A key aspect in pesticide multiresidue methods is their selectivity. The definition of this term is being revised by IUPAC, 11 who recommend its use for referring to the extent to which a given method can determine particular analytes under given conditions in mixtures or matrices, simple or complex, without interferences from other components. In the context of pesticide multiresidue methods the definition of selectivity relates to the matrix effects and/or the presence of interferences. Massart et al. 12 distinguish between interferences (for example, co-elution of two compounds in a chromatographic method) and matrix effects, which may affect the analytical signal by increasing the level of random errors and/or introducing a systematic effect on the analytical results (which can be either constant, affecting the blank, or proportional, affecting the analytical sensitivity).
 ###### 
From cou.: 5 In pesticide multiresidue methods selectivities based on multistage separation and detection principles are frequently used. The extraction step has to be general enough to allow quantitative extraction of pesticides with different chemical and physical properties, in the literature screening methods are described using solvents1–4,10 such as ethyl acetate, acetone, petroleum ether and dichloromethane or the use of supercritical fluid extraction.13 With regard to the determination step, chromatographic techniques with different detectors, such as gas or liquid, are the most used due to their capability for separating a wide range of analytes in a single run.
From Soup: 5 In pesticide multiresidue methods selectivities based on multistage separation and detection principles are frequently used. The extraction step has to be general enough to allow quantitative extraction of pesticides with different chemical and physical properties, in the literature screening methods are described using solvents 1–4,10 such as ethyl acetate , acetone , petroleum ether and dichloromethane or the use of supercritical fluid extraction . 13 With regard to the determination step, chromatographic techniques with different detectors, such as gas or liquid, are the most used due to their capability for separating a wide range of analytes in a single run.
 ###### 
From cou.: 6 Several authors refer to the nature of matrix effects as a ‘protection’ of the analytes from adsorption and/or decomposition mainly in the injection ports of gas chromatography (GC) systems.14,15 Matrix effects in such methods can be reduced in the sample processing step by using clean-up methods.16,17 Chromatographic techniques tend to rely for selectivity on the separation process, or even on the combination of the selectivities achieved with respect to the detection and separation,16 in this sense hyphenated techniques, such as GC-MS or the extended GC-MS-MS, yield an especially high selectivity.11,18
From Soup: 6 Several authors refer to the nature of matrix effects as a ‘protection’ of the analytes from adsorption and/or decomposition mainly in the injection ports of gas chromatography ( GC ) systems. 14,15 Matrix effects in such methods can be reduced in the sample processing step by using clean-up methods. 16,17 Chromatographic techniques tend to rely for selectivity on the separation process, or even on the combination of the selectivities achieved with respect to the detection and separation, 16 in this sense hyphenated techniques, such as GC-MS or the extended GC-MS-MS, yield an especially high selectivity. 11,18
 ###### 
From cou.: 7 However, most routine laboratories tend to minimise the experimental work, avoiding steps such as clean-up (when possible) due to their time-consuming nature and to the likely increase in the uncertainty in the results that each additional step in the analytical process might bring about; hyphenated techniques are also still expensive for many laboratories.
From Soup: 7 However, most routine laboratories tend to minimise the experimental work, avoiding steps such as clean-up (when possible) due to their time-consuming nature and to the likely increase in the uncertainty in the results that each additional step in the analytical process might bring about; hyphenated techniques are also still expensive for many laboratories.
 ###### 
From cou.: 8 Despite the use of such measures matrix effects can still affect the analytical results..14,19–22 The inclusion of matrix co-extractives in the calibration step is a way of minimising the effects of the matrix in the quantification of pesticides. For this, the use of a standard additions method is suggested in the literature,12,23 but the most usual and recommended way to avoid such matrix effects is the use of matrix-matched calibration.23–26 Nevertheless, this measure is again time-consuming and it does not give any information about the extent of such effects.
From Soup: 8 Despite the use of such measures matrix effects can still affect the analytical results.. 14,19–22 The inclusion of matrix co-extractives in the calibration step is a way of minimising the effects of the matrix in the quantification of pesticides . For this, the use of a standard additions method is suggested in the literature, 12,23 but the most usual and recommended way to avoid such matrix effects is the use of matrix-matched calibration. 23–26 Nevertheless, this measure is again time-consuming and it does not give any information about the extent of such effects.
 ###### 
From cou.: 9 This paper presents a methodology for assessing the matrix effects of eight different vegetable commodities for the quantification of eight pesticides that are analysed by GC using a nitrogen–phosphorus detector (GC-NPD). A statistical treatment allows the estimation of the matrix effects by comparison of calibration curves prepared in solvent and in blank vegetable extracts (matrix-matched calibration). A correction function has been obtained in each case that allows reliable results to be obtained using solvent calibration for quantification. The correction functions have been validated, the uncertainty estimated and their robustness tested during a six month period in which only minor changes in the chromatographic conditions were made.
From Soup: 9 This paper presents a methodology for assessing the matrix effects of eight different vegetable commodities for the quantification of eight pesticides that are analysed by GC using a nitrogen–phosphorus detector ( GC-NPD ). A statistical treatment allows the estimation of the matrix effects by comparison of calibration curves prepared in solvent and in blank vegetable extracts (matrix-matched calibration). A correction function has been obtained in each case that allows reliable results to be obtained using solvent calibration for quantification. The correction functions have been validated, the uncertainty estimated and their robustness tested during a six month period in which only minor changes in the chromatographic conditions were made.
 ###### 
From cou.: 10 The analytical methodology presented in this work is being used as a routine method in a pesticide residues laboratory (Centro Universitario Analitico Municipal, CUAM) where more than 10000 samples are analysed each year. It is accredited to ISO 17025.
From Soup: 10 The analytical methodology presented in this work is being used as a routine method in a pesticide residues laboratory (Centro Universitario Analitico Municipal, CUAM) where more than 10000 samples are analysed each year. It is accredited to ISO 17025.
