From cou.: 13 A gas chromatograph Hewlett-Packard (Palo Alto, CA, USA) model 5890 equipped with a nitrogen–phosphorus detector (NPD) was used. The GC-NPD operating conditions were: injector temperature, 250 °C; detector temperature, 300 °C; splitless time, 2 min; initial oven temperature, 90 °C for 1 min, raised at 15 °C min−1 to 170 °C for 0 min, raised at 2 °C min−1 to 220 °C for 0 min, raised at 10 °C min−1 to 255 °C, and then held at 255°C for 5 min. The carrier gas was nitrogen at 1 mL min−1. A fused silica capillary (HP-1) column containing 100% methylpolysiloxane as stationary phase [60 m length, 0.25 mm internal diameter (id) and 0.25 µm film thickness] was used for the separation in the GC. The experiment performed in June was carried out in a different GC, with the same kind of column and by the same analyst.
From Soup: 13 A gas chromatograph Hewlett-Packard (Palo Alto, CA, USA) model 5890 equipped with a nitrogen–phosphorus detector ( NPD ) was used. The GC-NPD operating conditions were: injector temperature, 250 °C; detector temperature, 300 °C; splitless time, 2 min; initial oven temperature, 90 °C for 1 min, raised at 15 °C min −1 to 170 °C for 0 min, raised at 2 °C min −1 to 220 °C for 0 min, raised at 10 °C min −1 to 255 °C, and then held at 255°C for 5 min. The carrier gas was nitrogen at 1 mL min −1 . A fused silica capillary (HP-1) column containing 100% methylpolysiloxane as stationary phase [60 m length, 0.25 mm internal diameter (id) and 0.25 µm film thickness] was used for the separation in the GC. The experiment performed in June was carried out in a different GC, with the same kind of column and by the same analyst.
