From cou.: 22 In order to state the matrix effects and to obtain a correction function for each pesticide, a calibration solution prepared in solvent (SC) and a calibration solution prepared using blank matrix extracts (MC) instead of pure solvent were compared. The analyte concentrations in both kinds of standard solutions were the same: 0.20, 0.60, 1.00 and 1.40 mg L−1 for all the pesticides, except for ethoprophos and carbophenothion, which were 0.05, 0.15, 0.25 and 0.35 mg L−1 and for diazinon which were 0.10, 0.30, 0.50 and 0.70 mg L−1. These concentration ranges were chosen on the basis of the MRLs in vegetables allowed by European regulations for such pesticides in the studied commodities. In both kinds of calibration the calibration solutions were prepared by dilution with cyclohexane (pure in the case of SC and matrix-matched for each commodity in the case of MC), 50, 150, 250 and 350 µL of the secondary standard solution was added to 2 mL after adding the internal standard (caffeine at 1 mg L−1). 1 µL of these solutions was injected into the GC-NPD.
From Soup: 22 In order to state the matrix effects and to obtain a correction function for each pesticide , a calibration solution prepared in solvent (SC) and a calibration solution prepared using blank matrix extracts (MC) instead of pure solvent were compared. The analyte concentrations in both kinds of standard solutions were the same: 0.20, 0.60, 1.00 and 1.40 mg L −1 for all the pesticides , except for ethoprophos and carbophenothion , which were 0.05, 0.15, 0.25 and 0.35 mg L −1 and for diazinon which were 0.10, 0.30, 0.50 and 0.70 mg L −1 . These concentration ranges were chosen on the basis of the MRLs in vegetables allowed by European regulations for such pesticides in the studied commodities. In both kinds of calibration the calibration solutions were prepared by dilution with cyclohexane (pure in the case of SC and matrix-matched for each commodity in the case of MC), 50, 150, 250 and 350 µL of the secondary standard solution was added to 2 mL after adding the internal standard ( caffeine at 1 mg L −1 ). 1 µL of these solutions was injected into the GC-NPD.
