From cou.: 26 Fig. 2 show the statistical approach for assessing the matrix effects and the Appendix shows the different statistical formulae used for calculating each parameter. The experiments were repeated every month between June and September. Data for each replicate were fitted to straight lines using a least squares method28,29 obtaining an equation for each replicate. In the first step, the analysis of co-variance (ANCOVA)30was applied to the daily replicates of SC and MC in order to check their repeatability during a single day. Such analysis consisted of comparing the slopes using an F-test. If the calculated F value (Fcal) was less than the tabulated F value (Ftab), considering a 95% confidence, the slopes of the replicates did not differ. The same procedure was applied to the intercepts in order to check if the replicates are coincident or parallel. Fcal was also less than Ftab. Thus it could be concluded that neither solvent nor matrix calibration changed during the period of time taken for each batch to be analysed.
From Soup: 26 Fig. 2 show the statistical approach for assessing the matrix effects and the Appendix shows the different statistical formulae used for calculating each parameter. The experiments were repeated every month between June and September. Data for each replicate were fitted to straight lines using a least squares method 28,29 obtaining an equation for each replicate. In the first step, the analysis of co-variance (ANCOVA) 30 was applied to the daily replicates of SC and MC in order to check their repeatability during a single day. Such analysis consisted of comparing the slopes using an F -test. If the calculated F value ( F cal ) was less than the tabulated F value ( F tab ), considering a 95% confidence, the slopes of the replicates did not differ. The same procedure was applied to the intercepts in order to check if the replicates are coincident or parallel. F cal was also less than F tab . Thus it could be concluded that neither solvent nor matrix calibration changed during the period of time taken for each batch to be analysed.
