From cou.: 27 Under such conditions, a unique regression can be fitted by least squares regression both for SC and for each MC using the twelve data obtained in each calibration set (three replicates at each concentration level). ANCOVA was applied again, but in this case to compare the new calibration curves (SC versus MC) calculating F-statistics for both the slopes and the intercepts.
From Soup: 27 Under such conditions, a unique regression can be fitted by least squares regression both for SC and for each MC using the twelve data obtained in each calibration set (three replicates at each concentration level). ANCOVA was applied again, but in this case to compare the new calibration curves (SC versus MC) calculating F -statistics for both the slopes and the intercepts.
 ###### 
From cou.: 28 The ANCOVA was applied independently to the data obtained in each monthly experiment, the same conclusions were obtained in all cases. As an example Table 1 shows the Fcal values for the experiment carried out in June. It can be seen that the slopes do not differ statistically for chlorpyrifos-methyl in pepper, ethoprophos in watermelon and parathion-methyl in pepper and courgette (Fcal is minor than Ftab ), in such cases the intercepts were also statistically similar, which means that the above matrices do not exert any effect in the quantification of ethoprophos and parathion-methyl. In the case of chlorpyrifos-methyl in watermelon, similar slopes were obtained but the intercepts differ so that in this particular case a systematic bias affects the quantification of the analyte (Fig. 2). In the rest of the cases the Fcal results were higher than the Ftab values for both the slopes and the intercepts (Table 1), this indicates that there is a significant difference between the solvent and matrix-matched calibrations, which means that the matrix content introduces both a proportional and a systematic bias into the quantification of such residues.
From Soup: 28 The ANCOVA was applied independently to the data obtained in each monthly experiment, the same conclusions were obtained in all cases. As an example Table 1 shows the F cal values for the experiment carried out in June. It can be seen that the slopes do not differ statistically for chlorpyrifos- methyl in pepper, ethoprophos in watermelon and parathion-methyl in pepper and courgette ( F cal is minor than F tab ), in such cases the intercepts were also statistically similar, which means that the above matrices do not exert any effect in the quantification of ethoprophos and parathion-methyl . In the case of chlorpyrifos- methyl in watermelon, similar slopes were obtained but the intercepts differ so that in this particular case a systematic bias affects the quantification of the analyte ( Fig. 2 ). In the rest of the cases the F cal results were higher than the F tab values for both the slopes and the intercepts ( Table 1 ), this indicates that there is a significant difference between the solvent and matrix -matched calibrations, which means that the matrix content introduces both a proportional and a systematic bias into the quantification of such residues.
