From cou.: 29 A correction function (CF) was calculated each month from the slopes and intercepts of the unique regressions fitted for the SC and MC in each experiment. Both kinds of plots can be correlated using a linear correction function, CCF = A + B·CSC, where CSC is the concentration of spiked samples calculated by SC; CCF is the concentration obtained after applying the correction to the above results; and A and B are the correction coefficients, which are calculated from the regression coefficients of each calibration plot (see Appendix, eqns. (1) and (2)). A CF is then obtained as the mean average of the correction coefficients obtained in June, July, August and September (CCF = Ā + ·CSC). Table 2 shows the correction functions obtained for each pesticide in the different matrices.
From Soup: 29 A correction function (CF) was calculated each month from the slopes and intercepts of the unique regressions fitted for the SC and MC in each experiment. Both kinds of plots can be correlated using a linear correction function, C CF = A + B·C SC , where C SC is the concentration of spiked samples calculated by SC; C CF is the concentration obtained after applying the correction to the above results; and A and B are the correction coefficients, which are calculated from the regression coefficients of each calibration plot (see Appendix, eqns. (1) and (2) ). A CF is then obtained as the mean average of the correction coefficients obtained in June, July, August and September ( C CF = Ā + · C SC ). Table 2 shows the correction functions obtained for each pesticide in the different matrices.
 ###### 
From cou.: 30 The reliability of the use of CFs for avoiding the bias introduced by matrix effects in the quantification of pesticides, was tested by quantifying the same spiked samples with both SC and MC and by applying the CFs to the results obtained with SC. The recovery rates31,32 were calculated as the quotients between the amounts of analyte found in each of the three ways (CSC, CMC and CCF, respectively) and the spiked amount (see Appendix, eqns. (3), (4) and (5)). Tables 3 and 4 show the recovery rates obtained with SC and MC. It can be seen that the values are different, and by applying a t-test to the mean of the recovery rates (Appendix, eqn (6)), it was found that when SC was used, the recovery rates are statistically different to the 100% recovery (tcal > ttab), whereas when MC was used the recovery rates are similar to the 100% recovery (tcal is less than ttab), which means that MC is an effective way of avoiding matrix effects in order to obtain accurate results.
From Soup: 30 The reliability of the use of CFs for avoiding the bias introduced by matrix effects in the quantification of pesticides , was tested by quantifying the same spiked samples with both SC and MC and by applying the CFs to the results obtained with SC. The recovery rates 31,32 were calculated as the quotients between the amounts of analyte found in each of the three ways ( C SC , C MC and C CF , respectively) and the spiked amount (see Appendix, eqns. (3) , (4) and (5) ). Tables 3 and 4 show the recovery rates obtained with SC and MC. It can be seen that the values are different, and by applying a t -test to the mean of the recovery rates (Appendix, eqn (6) ), it was found that when SC was used, the recovery rates are statistically different to the 100% recovery ( t cal > t tab ), whereas when MC was used the recovery rates are similar to the 100% recovery ( t cal is less than t tab ), which means that MC is an effective way of avoiding matrix effects in order to obtain accurate results.
 ###### 
From cou.: 31 Finally, the results obtained after applying the correction function to the results obtained with SC were compared with a paired sample test. It was concluded that any statistical difference observed between both methods had a probability of greater than 5%. As shown in Table 5, tcal was less than ttab, and therefore there was no significant difference between the recovery rates obtained with MC and CF.
From Soup: 31 Finally, the results obtained after applying the correction function to the results obtained with SC were compared with a paired sample test. It was concluded that any statistical difference observed between both methods had a probability of greater than 5%. As shown in Table 5 , t cal was less than t tab , and therefore there was no significant difference between the recovery rates obtained with MC and CF.
