From cou.: 33 The Appendix show the calculation used to obtain the uncertainty27 associated with the estimation of the concentration using CF, u(CCF). It was calculated by applying the variance propagation rules to such estimation and by considering the different uncertainty sources, the uncertainty associated with the estimated concentration, CCF, can be calculated, following the variance propagation rules, as (Appendix, eqn (7)):It can be seen that the uncertainty u(CCF) relies upon the uncertainty due to the correction coefficients A and B, u(A) and u(B), respectively, and the uncertainty due to the covariance between the slope and intercept, rA,B (Appendix, eqns. (8), (9) and (10)). The terms u(A) and u(B) are calculated as the contributions derived from the regression line, u(A)func, u(B)func, and the uncertainty derived from the precision, u(A)prec and u(B)prec (Appendix, eqns. (11) and (12)).
From Soup: 33 The Appendix show the calculation used to obtain the uncertainty 27 associated with the estimation of the concentration using CF, u ( C CF ). It was calculated by applying the variance propagation rules to such estimation and by considering the different uncertainty sources, the uncertainty associated with the estimated concentration, C CF , can be calculated, following the variance propagation rules, as (Appendix, eqn (7) ): It can be seen that the uncertainty u ( C CF ) relies upon the uncertainty due to the correction coefficients A and B , u ( A ) and u ( B ), respectively, and the uncertainty due to the covariance between the slope and intercept, r A , B (Appendix, eqns. (8) , (9) and (10) ). The terms u ( A ) and u ( B ) are calculated as the contributions derived from the regression line, u ( A ) func , u ( B ) func , and the uncertainty derived from the precision, u ( A ) prec and u ( B ) prec (Appendix, eqns. (11) and (12) ).
 ###### 
From cou.: 34 Finally, the uncertainty associated with the correction function is obtained as the sum of all the above contributions, resulting in a second degree equation that depends only upon CSC for a given value of uncertainty u(CSC). It can be seen that if CSC increases, the uncertainty also increases. Table 2 shows the uncertainty obtained in each case considering u(CSC) = 11% for all pesticides,27 it can be observed that the use of the correction function increases the uncertainty of results by less than 11%; the global uncertainty is in most cases less than 20%. With the use of the correction function one can suppose results of between 40 and 70% of the global uncertainty, such a value is within the uncertainty commonly accepted in the field of pesticide residue analysis.
