From cou.: 35 The effects of co-extractives from eight different vegetable commodities in the quantification of pesticides by GC-NPD have been assessed. The methodology proposed consists of comparing the calibration curves prepared in solvent with those prepared in a blank matrix extract by using ANCOVA, a useful statistical tool for such a purpose. This study concluded that matrix effects lead, in most cases, to both systematic and proportional bias in the quantification of the pesticides if a solvent calibration is used for the determinations.
From Soup: 35 The effects of co-extractives from eight different vegetable commodities in the quantification of pesticides by GC-NPD have been assessed. The methodology proposed consists of comparing the calibration curves prepared in solvent with those prepared in a blank matrix extract by using ANCOVA, a useful statistical tool for such a purpose. This study concluded that matrix effects lead, in most cases, to both systematic and proportional bias in the quantification of the pesticides if a solvent calibration is used for the determinations.
 ###### 
From cou.: 36 A correction function for correcting the matrix effects in each commodity has been proposed. The correction functions obtained showed good stability over a period of four months where only minor changes in the working conditions occurred, such as reagent batches and chromatographic maintenance. A paired sample t-test showed that there was no statistical difference between the results achieved using a matrix-matched calibration and those obtained after applying the correction function to the data obtained with solvent calibration. The use of the correction function might lead to a saving in costs and in the time taken for the analyses in pesticide residue laboratories, by avoiding the need for the extraction of blank samples, saving solvents, enlarging the life of the chromatographic consumables and by making easier the quantification with the use of simple solvent calibration.
From Soup: 36 A correction function for correcting the matrix effects in each commodity has been proposed. The correction functions obtained showed good stability over a period of four months where only minor changes in the working conditions occurred, such as reagent batches and chromatographic maintenance. A paired sample t -test showed that there was no statistical difference between the results achieved using a matrix-matched calibration and those obtained after applying the correction function to the data obtained with solvent calibration. The use of the correction function might lead to a saving in costs and in the time taken for the analyses in pesticide residue laboratories, by avoiding the need for the extraction of blank samples, saving solvents , enlarging the life of the chromatographic consumables and by making easier the quantification with the use of simple solvent calibration.
 ###### 
From cou.: 37 Finally, an estimation of the uncertainty associated with the use of the correction function showed, in all cases, that the additional uncertainty in the results is less than 11%, except for carbophenothion in tomato and pepper, and parathion-ethyl in tomato which is 15%, which is less than that associated with other steps of the analytical method, such as the calibration step.
